The constant term of a binomial expansion is found by identifying the term where the powers of $$x$$ and $$\dfrac{1}{3x}$$ cancel each other out, leaving a term without $$x$$. This occurs when we have a specific combination of these terms that results in a constant. The general term of the expansion is given by $$\binom{6}{k}(6x)^{6-k}\left(\dfrac{1}{3x}\right)^k$$, where $$\binom{6}{k}$$ is the binomial coefficient. To obtain a constant term, we need the powers of $$x$$ to cancel out, which happens when $$6-k-k=0$$, leading to $$k=3$$. Therefore, the constant term is determined by the term where $$k=3$$. Since $$6-3=3$$, we get $$\binom{6}{3}(6)^{6-3}\left(\dfrac{1}{3}\right)^3$$. Simplifying, we have $$\binom{6}{3}(6^3)\left(\dfrac{1}{3^3}\right) = 20 \cdot 216 \cdot \dfrac{1}{27} = 160$.\rtheta
